\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Consider a group with three elements.
 One of them must be the unique identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

; call the others 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 All elements need to have a unique inverse, so the possibilities are 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-1}=c$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-1}=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $bc$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $bc=1$
\end_inset

, then this is the 
\begin_inset Formula $c=b^{-1};\ b^{-1}=c$
\end_inset

 case, and all is well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $bc=b$
\end_inset

 (without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $cb=c$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}bc=b^{-1}b\rightarrow c=1$
\end_inset

 (without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1$
\end_inset

).
