\series default
.
 
\emph on
Theorem
\emph default
.
 A finite group is the union of proper subgroups iff it is not cyclic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

) Suppose that finite group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 were the union of proper subgroups: 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\bigcup_{i}H_{i};\ \forall i\ H_{i}\le G$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 were cyclic.
 Then it would be generated by a single element; call it 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, all elements of the group are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g^{k}:k\in\mathbb{Z}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 But subgroups are closed under the operation, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g^{k}:k\in\mathbb{Z}\}\subseteq H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not a proper subgroup after all: contradiction! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset Formula $\Leftarrow$
\end_inset

) Suppose by way of contraposition that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not the union of proper subgroups.
 Then there must be an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 that is not in any subgroup smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 itself.
 So the subgroup generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must be the entire group, 
\emph on
i.e
\emph default
., a cyclic group.
 
\end_layout

